CAPE TOWN - The Guptas faced more criminal charges following revelations that taxpayers' money was used to pay for a lavish family wedding at Sun City in 2013. The DA said it would open a case at the Cape Town police station on Monday. The latest #GuptaLeaks emails revealed that the Free State provincial government largely picked up the tab for the four-day nuptials of Vega Gupta and Aakash Jahajgarhia, to the tune of R30-million.An AmaBhungane investigative report showed the money was meant for a diary farm empowerment project, but was diverted through shell companies to pay for the wedding.READ: #GuptaLeaks: The Dubai Laundromat - How millions from dairy paid for Sun City wedding In a statement on Sunday, DA Shadow Minister of Finance, David Maynier, said he would lay criminal charges against Atul Gupta, Ajay Gupta, Rajesh Gupta, Ronica Ragavan and Kamal Vasram.Ragavan was the acting CEO of the Guptas' Oakbay Investments, while Vasram was a former employee of a Gupta-owned company. "The fact that public funds, which were meant to assist the poor, were allegedly used by President Jacob Zuma s most important clients, the Guptas, to pay for a family wedding is grotesque and must be investigated by the South African Police Service," the statement said. It comes after the DA in May laid treason charges against Zuma, the Guptas and several ministers, following the publication of the first #GuptaLeaks reports.Meanwhile, auditing firm, KPMG, denied it helped to hide the R30-million while it was still auditors for the Guptas' businesses. eNCA